---
import PageLayout from "@layouts/PageLayout.astro";
import Container from "@components/Container.astro";
import FormattedDate from "@components/FormattedDate.astro";
import BackToPrev from "@components/BackToPrev.astro";

const title = "Data Lakehouse Research";
const description =
  "A short research note on the Data Lakehouse architecture: motivation, open table formats, and how it sits between the Data Warehouse and the Data Lake.";
const date = new Date("2026-04-25");
const readingTimeLabel = "8 min read";
---

<PageLayout title={title} description={description}>
  <Container>
    <div class="animate">
      <BackToPrev href="/papers">
        Back to papers
      </BackToPrev>
    </div>

    <div class="space-y-1 my-10">
      <div class="animate flex items-center gap-1.5">
        <div class="font-base text-sm">
          <FormattedDate date={date} />
        </div>
        &bull;
        <div class="font-base text-sm">
          {readingTimeLabel}
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="animate text-2xl font-semibold text-black dark:text-white">
        {title}
      </div>
    </div>

    <article class="animate">
      <blockquote>
        The <strong>Data Lakehouse</strong> combines the low-cost, flexible
        storage of a data lake with the transactional guarantees and
        performance of a data warehouse.
      </blockquote>

      <h2>Background</h2>
      <p>
        Traditional analytics stacks evolved in two stages. The
        <strong>Data Warehouse</strong> gave us ACID transactions, schema
        enforcement, and fast SQL, but at a high cost and with weak support
        for unstructured data. The <strong>Data Lake</strong>, built on cheap
        object storage such as S3, GCS, or ADLS, handles raw and
        semi-structured data at scale, but sacrifices correctness and query
        performance.
      </p>
      <p>
        Most organizations ended up with a two-tier architecture: a lake for
        raw and ML workloads, and a warehouse for BI. That duplication causes
        staleness, extra cost, and governance pain. The lakehouse targets
        exactly that problem by bringing warehouse-like capabilities directly
        onto the lake.
      </p>

      <h2>Core ideas</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>
          Data stays in open columnar files (Parquet, ORC) on object storage.
        </li>
        <li>
          A transactional metadata layer sits on top of those files and
          provides ACID, schema evolution, and time travel.
        </li>
        <li>
          Storage and compute are decoupled, so multiple engines (Spark,
          Trino, Flink, DuckDB) can read and write the same table.
        </li>
        <li>
          BI, streaming, data science, and ML all target a single source of
          truth instead of separate copies.
        </li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Open table formats</h2>

      <h3>Delta Lake</h3>
      <p>
        Originated at Databricks. Uses a transaction log
        (<code>_delta_log</code>) with JSON and checkpoint Parquet files to
        record atomic commits over the data. Strong ecosystem around Spark
        and Databricks, with growing support in Trino, Flink, and DuckDB.
      </p>

      <h3>Apache Iceberg</h3>
      <p>
        Designed at Netflix for very large tables. Uses a hierarchical
        metadata tree (metadata file, manifest list, manifests) to support
        partition evolution, hidden partitioning, and consistent snapshots.
        Engine-agnostic, and increasingly the de facto standard in
        multi-engine environments.
      </p>

      <h3>Apache Hudi</h3>
      <p>
        Built at Uber around streaming-first ingestion. Offers two table
        types &mdash; Copy-on-Write and Merge-on-Read &mdash; that trade
        write amplification against read latency. A natural fit for
        incremental pipelines and CDC.
      </p>

      <h2>Warehouse vs. Lake vs. Lakehouse</h2>
      <table>
        <thead>
          <tr>
            <th>Aspect</th>
            <th>Warehouse</th>
            <th>Lake</th>
            <th>Lakehouse</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr>
            <td>Storage</td>
            <td>Proprietary</td>
            <td>Open files</td>
            <td>Open files + table format</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>ACID</td>
            <td>Yes</td>
            <td>No</td>
            <td>Yes</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Schema</td>
            <td>Strong</td>
            <td>Weak</td>
            <td>Strong + evolution</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>ML / unstructured</td>
            <td>Limited</td>
            <td>Excellent</td>
            <td>Excellent</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td>Cost</td>
            <td>High</td>
            <td>Low</td>
            <td>Low &ndash; Medium</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2>Closing thoughts</h2>
      <p>
        The lakehouse is not a silver bullet, but it is a credible path
        toward one copy of the data for analytics, ML, and streaming. For
        teams still running a classic lake-plus-warehouse stack, adopting an
        open table format is the cheapest, lowest-risk first step.
      </p>

      <h2>References</h2>
      <ol>
        <li>
          Armbrust, M. et al. &mdash; <em>Lakehouse: A New Generation of Open
          Platforms that Unify Data Warehousing and Advanced Analytics</em>,
          CIDR, 2021.
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="https://delta.io" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
            Delta Lake documentation
          </a>
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="https://iceberg.apache.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
            Apache Iceberg
          </a>
        </li>
        <li>
          <a href="https://hudi.apache.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
            Apache Hudi
          </a>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </article>
  </Container>
</PageLayout>
